@node "installation" "Installing Mathador      "
@prev "introduction"
@{bg shine}Installing Mathador could not be easier!@{bg back}

1. Reading the guide means that you already extracted all files
   from the archive "MathadorV1.1.lha" from Aminet. During the
   extraction a new drawer "MathInstall" was created.

2. If the whole distribution (all files and directories) is in the
   new drawer "MathInstall" open that drawers window.

3. There are two possibilities to install Mathador:

a. You can use the installer script "@{fg shine}Install_Mathador@{fg text}" which
   uses the standard installer (the easiest way for everybody).
   An icon for "Install_Mathador" is in "MathInstall". Just
   click twice on this icon. Further reading at item 4.

b. Or you can install Mathador using an AmigaDOS-script:
   You will recognize an icon called "InstallMath".
   If you double-click on "InstallMath", Mathador will
   be installed on a system with Workbench 2.0 or higher.
   The destination drive will be "Work:".

   If you do not want to install Mathador on the drive "Work:",
   you can do the following:
   Click once on the icon InstallMath. Then press the Shift-key
   and click twice on the destination drawer or volume. Mathador
   will be installed in this destination.

   You can also give the shell-commands:

   "@{fg shine}cd SRC:MathInstall@{fg text}"
   "@{fg shine}execute InstallMath DEST:@{fg text}"

   where "SRC:" is the drive which contains the drawer
   "MathInstall", and "DEST:" is your destination drive.
   On "DEST:" the drawer "Mathador" will be created.

4. The install script copies the "reqtools.library" and
   the "mathador.library" to "LIBS:".

5. You can delete the drawer (or directory) "MathInstall" if
   the installation was successful, i.e. if no error occurred.

6. The program Mathador can be found in the newly created
   drawer Mathador on "Work:" or "DEST:".
@endnode

@node "start_math" "Starting Mathador V1.1"
@prev "installation"
@{bg shine}Starting Mathador V1.1:@{bg back}

There are two possible ways to start the program Mathador:

1. Double-click on the icon "Mathador" in the drawer "Mathador".

   The following TOOLTYPES are available:

   FONT              defines your preferred font for Mathador.
                     e.g. "FONT=GoldEd.font" sets the font to
                     the GoldEd font. The appearance of all
                     windows will be recalculated when using
                     a new font.

   FONTSIZE          defines the size of the font to use.
                     e.g. "FONTSIZE=10" sets the size to 10.

   FONTREQ           if set to 1 opens the fontrequester every
                     time Mathador is started from Workbench.
                     The font from the requester has priority
                     over the font set from TOOLTYPE FONT.
                     e.g. "FONTREQ=0": no requester appears.
                     This feature needs Kickstart 3.0+.

   SCREENMODEREQ     if set to 1 opens the screenmode requester
                     every time Mathador is started from WB.
                     The screenmode from the requester has
                     priority over the TOOLTYPE SCREENID.
                     "SCREENMODEREQ=0" shows no requester.
                     This feature needs Kickstart 3.0+.

   SCREENWIDTH       defines the width of the desired screen
                     for Kickstart 2.0 users. e.g.
                     "SCREENWIDTH=800" sets the width to 800 pixels.

   SCREENHEIGHT      defines the height of the desired screen
                     for Kickstart 2.0 users, e.g.
                     "SCREENHEIGHT=600" sets the height to 600 pixels.

   SCREENID          defines the Screen ID for Kickstart 2.0 users.
                     The ID must be given in hexadecimal.
                     e.g. "SCREENID=0x19004" sets the screenmode
                     to NTSC: HighRes Lace.


2. Open a shell-window, change to the directory which contains
   the program (e.g. with "cd Work:Mathador") and enter
   "Mathador" (or give the whole pathname in front).
   You should have set the stack to at least 50000 Bytes.

   To show the command options you can give the command
   "Mathador -h" or "Mathador ?".


While the program Mathador starts, it reads a file called "Mathador.pref",
which contains all settings and calculations last used. A second file
"Mathador.cfg" which contains the preferred screen and font settings is read,
too. This file will be newly written reflecting all screen and font changes
when closing Mathador.

@{fg shine}@{bg text}NOTE:@{fg text}@{bg back} If "@{fg shine}Mathador.cfg@{fg text}" is present, @{fg shine}an initial screenmode requester@{fg text} will
appear only if TOOLTYPE "SCREENMODEREQ=1" is set. If you want to change your
preferred screenmode for the program, set this TOOLTYPE to 1, and start
Mathador afterwards.
@endnode

@node "arexx" "The ARexx Port of Mathador V1.1"
@prev "print_diagrs"
@{bg shine}The ARexx port of Mathador V1.1:@{bg back}

Mathador's ARexx port offers all the functionality of the main window and all
subwindows, and more besides.

The first @{b}portname@{ub} is "Mathador.Host", all next ports are called
"Mathador.Host_nn", where "nn" is a two digit number. If the second Mathador
process is meant, "nn" should be 01, for the third process "nn" = 02, and so
on.

An @{b}alphabetical list@{ub} of all the commands that Mathador supports is available
as a registered user.


Using the ARexx port will allow you to interface Mathador with other
scientific programs, for example the scientific laboratory program PolyGraph.
PolyGraph is available on Aminet, too (look for PolyLab20.0.lha in misc/math).
@endnode

@node "arexx_examples" "ARexx example scripts     "
@prev "arexx"
@{bg shine}ARexx example script:@{bg back}

An example script is in the drawer Mathador. To use this script choose the
menu item 'ARexx/Execute Macro...' and choose the script you want to check. At
the moment only the following script is available:

   @{"TestMath-01.rexx" link "TestMath-01.rexx" 0}       Short Test of ARexx capabilities
@endnode

@node "manual" "Getting the manual V1.1        "
@next "how_to_contact"
@prev "distribution"
@{bg shine}How to get the full guide to Mathador:@{bg back}

You should first pay the fee to get the @{"registered version" link "distribution" 0} of Mathador. You
will get a disk containing the full manual in AmigaGuide-format, and possibly
in TeX-format.

Registered users will also get a description of the "@{fg shine}mathador.library@{fg text}" and its
functions, so that they can use the library in C-programs of their own. The
"@{fg shine}mathador.library@{fg text}" offers a rich set of complex mathematical functions
including complex Besselfunctions, complex Fresnel integrals, complete
Elliptic integrals, and much more.

@{fg shine}@{bg shadow}NOTE:@{fg text}@{bg back} If there are not enough registered users, it will not worth the time to
write a guide covering all aspects of Mathador including its complex
scientific functions and ARexx capabilities. Therefore it is possible, that as
a registered user you will get the complete program, but the guide does not
cover the whole thing. Please contact the author if there are any problems
concerning the use of Mathador.
@endnode

